<?php $__env->startSection('content'); ?><p>Leeds could be the latest city added to the government's coronavirus watchlist, leaving nearly half-a-million people in city facing the possibility of tighter lockdown restrictions, as infection rates continue to rise.</p>

<p>New figures show the West Yorkshire city's seven day infection rate has risen to 29.4 cases for every 100,000 people in the city - moving it on to a list with some of worst affected cities in the UK.</p>

<p>Today, council chiefs in the city have revealed they expect to be put on Public Health England's coronavirus watchlist, which, although does not automatically mean restrictions will be in place, brings the possibility of new local lockdown measures one step closer.</p>

<p>Council bosses say an increase in coronavirus cases among younger people across the city is to blame for the rise.</p>

<p>New figures show Leed's seven day infection rate has risen to 29.4 cases for every 100,000 people in the city - moving it on to a list with some of worst affected cities in the UK</p>

